On full project re-index, call `prune_deleted_files(root)` at the end to remove chunks for files that no longer exist on disk. This keeps the index clean without requiring a full rebuild.

The mtime approach is O(1) per file (one stat call + one SQLite lookup) vs content hashing which requires reading the entire file. For a typical project with 1000 files where 5 changed, this saves reading 995 files.

Fall back to a sliding window with overlap:

```rust
fn sliding_window_chunks(file_path: &str, lines: &[&str]) -> Vec<CodeChunk> {
    const WINDOW: usize = 40;
    const OVERLAP: usize = 10;
    let step = WINDOW.saturating_sub(OVERLAP).max(1);

    let mut chunks = Vec::new();
    let mut start = 0;

    while start < lines.len() {
        let end = (start + WINDOW).min(lines.len());
        let content = lines[start..end].join("\n");
        if !content.trim().is_empty() {
            chunks.push(CodeChunk {
                file_path: file_path.to_string(),
                chunk_type: ChunkType::Block,
                symbol_name: None,
                start_line: (start + 1) as u32,
                end_line: end as u32,
                content,
            });
        }
        if end == lines.len() { break; }
        start += step;
    }
    chunks
}
```

The 10-line overlap ensures that content near chunk boundaries isn't lost -- a function definition that starts at line 38 would appear in both the first chunk (lines 1-40) and the second chunk (lines 31-70). The embedding model can match queries against either occurrence.

Choose the boundary detector first, only fall back to sliding window when no patterns match. This handles config files, markdown, plain text, and languages the boundary detector doesn't know about.

The key is using sentence-ending punctuation *followed by whitespace* as the boundary, not just a period:

```rust
let raw: &[(&str, &'static str, f32)] = &[
    // Match until period+space, period+EOL, or newline
    (r"(?i)\bmy name is\s+(.+?)(?:[.;!]\s|[.;!]$|\n|$)", "user_name", 0.95),
    (r"(?i)\b(?:i use|we use)\s+(.+?)(?:[.;!]\s|[.;!]$|\n|$)", "tech_stack", 0.7),
    (r"(?i)\b(?:don't|never|avoid)\s+(.+?)(?:[.;!]\s|[.;!]$|\n|$)", "constraint", 0.85),
];
```

The pattern `(?:[.;!]\s|[.;!]$|\n|$)` means: stop at a period/semicolon/exclamation followed by whitespace OR at end-of-string OR at newline. This correctly handles:
- `"I use Node.js for the backend"` -> captures `"Node.js for the backend"` (period not followed by space)
- `"My name is Charlie. I use Rust."` -> captures `"Charlie"` (period followed by space)

Post-processing cleans the extracted value:
```rust
fn clean_value(raw: &str) -> String {
    let trimmed = raw.trim();
    let stripped = trimmed.trim_end_matches(|c: char| ".!?,;:".contains(c)).trim();
    let capped = if stripped.len() > 200 {
        let mut end = 200;
        while !stripped.is_char_boundary(end) { end -= 1; }  // Safe UTF-8 truncation
        &stripped[..end]
    } else { stripped };
    capped.to_string()
}
```

The 200-char cap with char boundary awareness prevents truncating multi-byte characters mid-sequence.

Two defenses: pattern design and input length limits.

**Pattern design**: Use lazy quantifiers (`.+?`) and anchor the stop condition to concrete characters:
```rust
// GOOD: lazy match with concrete stop
r"(?i)\bmy name is\s+(.+?)(?:[.;!]\s|[.;!]$|\n|$)"

// BAD: greedy match with backtracking
r"(?i)\bmy name is\s+(.+)[.;!]"
```

The good pattern advances character by character and checks the stop condition at each step. The bad pattern tries to match everything, fails, backtracks one character, tries again -- O(n^2) worst case.

**Input length cap**: Truncate before pattern matching:
```rust
let maxInputLength = 5000;
let truncated = if message.count > maxInputLength {
    String(message.prefix(maxInputLength))
} else { message };
```

