Three reasons: update safety, permissions, and sandboxing.

1. **Update safety**: Bundled knowledge (medical facts, coding conventions, etc.) ships inside the app bundle and gets updated with app releases. User facts (wife's name, preferred language) are personal data. If they lived in the same files, an app update that replaces bundle resources would wipe user data. Separation means updates never touch user files.

2. **macOS permissions**: The app bundle (`Bundle.main.resourceURL`) is code-signed and read-only after installation. Writing to it would break the signature and trigger Gatekeeper warnings. Application Support (`~/Library/Application Support/`) is the designated writable location for per-user data.

3. **Sandboxing**: On sandboxed macOS apps, the app can only write to its container. Application Support is inside the container. The bundle is read-only. Trying to write to the bundle would throw a permission error.

